<paragraph blockId="3.[178,1085,451,502]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">Until now the species was known only by male. In materials from my collection I found the female, which correspond well with the male and it is described below.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="1346" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[178,1086,517,715]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">
Female. Front wing 
<quantity box="[388,468,517,539]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346" unit="mm" value="4.5">4.5 mm</quantity>
, body 
<quantity box="[539,617,517,539]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.4" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346" unit="mm" value="5.4">5.4 mm</quantity>
long. Head strongly and rectilinear restricted behind (
<figureCitation box="[266,331,546,569]" captionStart="Figs 1-6" captionStartId="8.[178,218,1356,1378]" captionTargetBox="[179,1085,227,1321]" captionTargetId="figure-78@8.[178,1085,219,1348]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-6. Exochus hirsutus TOLKANITZ,: (1) head from above; (2) head in front; (3) front wing; (4) hind wing; (5) propodeum; (6) metasoma, lateral view. Figure Scale bars: 0.2 mm for 1,2,5; 0.5 mm for 3,4,6." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310245" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310245/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Interantennal procesus short. Antenna longer than half of the body. Flagellum with 27 elongated segments, postannellus 3.75 as long as wide, 11 
<superScript attach="left" box="[980,992,569,583]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">th</superScript>
segment 1.4 as long as wide. Eye irregularly elliptic, wider downwards. Inner eye orbitae weakly convergent down. Face and clypeus coarse punctured. Combined clypeus and face flat in lower part, face strongly convex in upper part, both conclude angle of 90 
<superScript attach="left" box="[978,988,656,671]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">○</superScript>
(
<figureCitation box="[1005,1072,664,686]" captionStart="Figs 1-6" captionStartId="8.[178,218,1356,1378]" captionTargetBox="[179,1085,227,1321]" captionTargetId="figure-78@8.[178,1085,219,1348]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-6. Exochus hirsutus TOLKANITZ,: (1) head from above; (2) head in front; (3) front wing; (4) hind wing; (5) propodeum; (6) metasoma, lateral view. Figure Scale bars: 0.2 mm for 1,2,5; 0.5 mm for 3,4,6." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310245" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310245/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Mouth wider than face. Malar space 0.4 as long as mandible base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[178,1086,730,898]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">
Notaulus short but distinct. Metapleurum without hairs, shining. Nervulus strongly inclival and postfurcal. First radius 3.0 as long as second radius (
<figureCitation box="[895,961,759,782]" captionStart="Figs 1-6" captionStartId="8.[178,218,1356,1378]" captionTargetBox="[179,1085,227,1321]" captionTargetId="figure-78@8.[178,1085,219,1348]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-6. Exochus hirsutus TOLKANITZ,: (1) head from above; (2) head in front; (3) front wing; (4) hind wing; (5) propodeum; (6) metasoma, lateral view. Figure Scale bars: 0.2 mm for 1,2,5; 0.5 mm for 3,4,6." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310245" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310245/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Nervellus strongly inclival, intercepted in lower 0.25 (
<figureCitation box="[648,715,789,811]" captionStart="Figs 1-6" captionStartId="8.[178,218,1356,1378]" captionTargetBox="[179,1085,227,1321]" captionTargetId="figure-78@8.[178,1085,219,1348]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-6. Exochus hirsutus TOLKANITZ,: (1) head from above; (2) head in front; (3) front wing; (4) hind wing; (5) propodeum; (6) metasoma, lateral view. Figure Scale bars: 0.2 mm for 1,2,5; 0.5 mm for 3,4,6." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310245" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310245/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Hind femur 2.1 as long as wide. Inner spur of hind tibia 0.6 as long as apical width of tibia. Correlation between hind tarsal segments as 21:12:9:7:13. Propodeum without costula. Basal area not separated from areola (
<figureCitation box="[309,371,876,898]" captionStart="Figs 1-6" captionStartId="8.[178,218,1356,1378]" captionTargetBox="[179,1085,227,1321]" captionTargetId="figure-78@8.[178,1085,219,1348]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-6. Exochus hirsutus TOLKANITZ,: (1) head from above; (2) head in front; (3) front wing; (4) hind wing; (5) propodeum; (6) metasoma, lateral view. Figure Scale bars: 0.2 mm for 1,2,5; 0.5 mm for 3,4,6." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310245" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310245/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Propodeal spiracle elongated. First and second lateral area haired.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[178,1085,914,965]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">
Dorsal carinae of first metasomal tergum developed to its middle. Ovipositor not bypass tip of metasoma (
<figureCitation box="[355,417,943,965]" captionStart="Figs 1-6" captionStartId="8.[178,218,1356,1378]" captionTargetBox="[179,1085,227,1321]" captionTargetId="figure-78@8.[178,1085,219,1348]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-6. Exochus hirsutus TOLKANITZ,: (1) head from above; (2) head in front; (3) front wing; (4) hind wing; (5) propodeum; (6) metasoma, lateral view. Figure Scale bars: 0.2 mm for 1,2,5; 0.5 mm for 3,4,6." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310245" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310245/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[178,1085,980,1152]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1346">Black; antenna from below, couple spots on vertex, face, clypeus, malar space, mandible, palpae, front coxa, apical half of middle coxa and tip of hind coxa from below yellow colored; legs red orange; femora yellow apically; hind tibia reddish, yellow in greater dorsal part, darkened in base and apically; flagellum from above and pterostigma dark brown. In the other as in male.</paragraph>
